#Uses piping to use multiple functions cleanly, and saves the result to a data frame called BoyNames
BoyNames <- BabyNames %>% 
  #only looks at boy names
  filter(sex == "boy") %>%
  #groups them by name
  group_by(name) %>%
  #finds the total percent for each group and calls this total popularity
  summarise(totalpopularity = sum(percent))  %>%
  #arranges the result in descending order of total popularity so most popular are at the top
  arrange(desc(totalpopularity))

#Creates a function to find the top 5 names of a data set, with an input called data
top5 <- function(data){
  #puts the data in descending order
  data <- data %>% 
    arrange(desc(percent))
  #saves only the first 5 rows
  data <- data[1:5,]
  #Creates a data frame with 6 columns, each with 1 entry of NA to correspond with the year and top 5 names, and saves this as names
  names <- data.frame("year" = NA, "firstname" = NA, "secondname" = NA, "thirdname" = NA, "fourthname" = NA, "fifthname" = NA)
  #sets the first entry (year) of names as the year of the first entry of the year column of the data, which will subsequently be the same for all entries because will group by year
  names[1] = data$year[1]
  #makes a for loop to set each entry of name, as the corresponding top name from the data set
  for(i in 1:5){
    names[i+1] <- data$name[i]
  }
  #returns the dataframe names
  return(names)
}

#Uses ddply to group BabyNames by year and sex, and then applies the function top5 to each of those groups, saving the resulting data to Top5names.  
Top5names<- ddply(.data = BabyNames, .(year, sex), .fun = top5)
#Shows the first 5 and last 5 entries of the data set

#Saves the csv file as a dataframe called data
data <- read.csv("http://people.math.umass.edu/~wei/Teaching/STAT597_Spring17/bnames.csv")

#Creates a funtion with an input called temp to find the linear regression model of that data 
lm.fit <- function(temp){
  #Uses lm() to find the linear regression model of percent as a function of year, and saves the model as fit
  fit <- lm(percent~year,data=temp) 
  #Returns a data frame where int is the intercept of the linear model, slope is the coefficient of year in the linear model, and n is the row dimension of the data aka the number of observations
  return(data.frame(int=fit$coef[1],slope=fit$coef[2],n=dim(temp)[1])) 
}

#Uses ddply() on the data, groups it by names and sex, and uses the lm.fit funtion on each group, and the result is saves as inc.dec.  
inc.dec <- ddply(data,.(name,sex),lm.fit)
#takes only those entries of inc.dec where n is greater than 100
inc.dec <- subset(inc.dec,n>100)
#takes only those entries of inc.dec where the slope is greater than the 99% quantile or less than the 1% quantile (the most extreme cases)
inc.dec <- subset(inc.dec,(slope>quantile(slope,p=0.99,na.rm=T))|
                    (slope<quantile(slope,p=0.01,na.rm=T)))

#Found function online, was treated almost like a package and the person said feel free to use it so assumed it was ok since we're allowed to use any package.  Takes plots and puts them together in a grid, with the specified number of columns (cols as an input).  
multiplot <- function(..., plotlist=NULL, file, cols=1, layout=NULL) {
  library(grid)
  
  # Make a list from the ... arguments and plotlist
  plots <- c(list(...), plotlist)
  
  numPlots = length(plots)
  
  # If layout is NULL, then use 'cols' to determine layout
  if (is.null(layout)) {
    # Make the panel
    # ncol: Number of columns of plots
    # nrow: Number of rows needed, calculated from # of cols
    layout <- matrix(seq(1, cols * ceiling(numPlots/cols)),
                     ncol = cols, nrow = ceiling(numPlots/cols))
  }
  
  if (numPlots==1) {
    print(plots[[1]])
    
  } else {
    # Set up the page
    grid.newpage()
    pushViewport(viewport(layout = grid.layout(nrow(layout), ncol(layout))))
    
    # Make each plot, in the correct location
    for (i in 1:numPlots) {
      # Get the i,j matrix positions of the regions that contain this subplot
      matchidx <- as.data.frame(which(layout == i, arr.ind = TRUE))
      
      print(plots[[i]], vp = viewport(layout.pos.row = matchidx$row,
                                      layout.pos.col = matchidx$col))
    }
  }
}















#This code is mine again
#Creates a function to graph the particular data set
graphfunc <- function(data){
  #creates a vector of years
  year <- c(1880:2008)
  #creates a graph where the year is the x axis and temporarily saves it as graph
  graph <- ggplot(data.frame(year), aes(year)) + 
    #plots the regression function
    stat_function(fun=function(year)(data$slope*year + data$int)) +
    #Creates x and y axis labels, a title, and sets the y-axis range so all the graphs have the same scale (years are already set)
    xlab("Year") + ylab("percent") + ggtitle(data$name) + ylim(-0.02,0.08)
  #Returns the graph created
  return(graph)
}

#Uses the dlply to group the data by name and the graphfunct created above to make a graph for each group, which is turned into a list and saved as graphs
graphs <- dlply(.data = inc.dec, .(name), .fun=graphfunc)

#uses the multiplot function to create a grid of the graphs saved in the list graphs, and sets the number of columns to 4
multiplot(plotlist = graphs, cols = 4)

#Creates a function to find the top 100 names of a data set with input called data
top100 <- function(data){
  #sorts the data in descending order by percent of babies with that name
  data <- data %>% 
    arrange(desc(percent))
  #Saves the top 100 entries as names
  names <- data[1:100,]
  #Returns those top 100 entries
  return(names)
}


#Groups the BabyNames by year and sex, and uses the function top100 on them to find the 100 names of each year for each gender and saves this to Top100names
Top100names<- ddply(.data = BabyNames, .(year, sex), .fun = top100)


#Takes those top 100 names and...
InTop100 <- Top100names %>%
  #groups them by year and sex and...
  group_by(year, sex) %>%
  #within each group, finds the sum of the percent of children with those names, which would be the percent of children per sex per year with names in the top 100
  summarise(PercInTop100 = sum(percent))
#Unloads all the packages to deal with issues between their interaction that wouldn't allow the file to knit
detach("package:ggplot2", unload = TRUE)
detach("package:dplyr", unload = TRUE)
detach("package:plyr", unload = TRUE)
## Warning: 'plyr' namespace cannot be unloaded:
##   namespace 'plyr' is imported by 'scales' so cannot be unloaded
#reloads ggplot2
library(ggplot2)
#Creates a plot of the data where year is the x axis, percent of baby names in the top 100 is the y access, and the data is grouped and colored by sex
ggplot(data = InTop100, aes(x= year, y=PercInTop100, group = sex, color = sex)) + 
  #puts points at each data point, and a line through it all
  geom_line() + geom_point(size = 0.5) +
  #labels the axes and title
  xlab("Year") + ylab("Percent of Children with Names in Top 100") + ggtitle("Percent of Children with Names in Top 100 By Year")
